@Node "M1_INTRD" "ImageDeskE.guide/M1_INTRD"
@Next "M2_REQUI"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

Introduction
************

ImageDesk is a program to  catalog  graphics  archives  by  generating
small   representations  of  pictures,  so  called  thumbnails.  Those
thumbnails are internally being expanded into  objects  which  include
all  essential  data of its represented picture. These can be combined
into loadable and savable thumbnail catalogs in which XPK  compression
is  supported  to  reduce  memory  consumption  on storage medias. The
catalogs are directory orientated, this  means  the  pictures  of  all
included  thumbnails  are  in  the  same directory path. the following
picture types are supported and will be recognized automatically:

   @{b}*@{ub} IFF ILBM (color mapped, EHB, HAM, HAM8, 24-Bit, DCOL )

   @{b}*@{ub} GIF (87a, 89a)

   @{b}*@{ub} JPEG (1)

   @{b}*@{ub} PCX (1 bit upto 32 bit)

   @{b}*@{ub} BMP (4,8 and 24 bit, OS/2 and Windows formats, unpacked only)

   @{b}*@{ub} PCD (upto BASE size)

   @{b}*@{ub} PNM (P4, P5 und P6)

   @{b}*@{ub} TARGA

   @{b}*@{ub} Amiga DATATYPES (picture class)

The corresponding picture of  a  thumbnail  object  can  be  shown  if
requested.  Therefore  two internal viewers, the window and the screen
viewer, exist for each internal supported format. The latter are  able
to  view  Images  on CyberGraphics, Picasso or standard 8 bit screens,
but it is also possible to specify external viewers or AREXX  programs
which ImageDesk will call on demand.

---------- Footnotes ----------

(1)  ImageDesk needs the "Tower JPEG Codec Class" from Christoph Feck
for its JPEG support.


@EndNode

@Node "M2_REQUI" "ImageDeskE.guide/M2_REQUI"
@Next "M3_INSTL"
@Prev "M1_INTRD"
@Toc "Main"

System Requirements
*******************

To figure a thumbnail image on the desk, ImageDesk needs an  Intuition
Screen  with  256  colors. Hence the minimum requirements of Kickstart
version is 3.0 (V39) or higher,  and  of  the  graphics  hardware  the
ability to provide 8-bit Intuition screens.

This distribution contains two versions of ImageDesk. One is  compiled
for  standard  systems  with  a  68000 CPU, the other version has been
optimized for 68020 processors, but should run on 030 and 040  systems
too. A coprocessor is not required (ImageDesk makes no use of floating
point arithmetic).

In quiet state the program allocates about 1MB of system  memory,  but
during  loading  or  generating  catalogs  the memory consumption will
increase drastically. For  calculating  the  thumbnail  images  it  is
necessary  to  extend all pixel data to a bitdepth of 24, additionally
catalogs are being held  in  a  buffer,  therefore  at  least  4MB  of
continous memory is recommended.


@EndNode

@Node "M3_INSTL" "ImageDeskE.guide/M3_INSTL"
@Next "M4_FASTE"
@Prev "M2_REQUI"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
************

The installation procedure is handled completely by the Installer. You
just   have   to   double-click   one   of   the   @{b}Install.Deutsch@{ub}  or
@{b}Install.English@{ub} icons in the ImageDesk drawer.

To install the "Tower  JPEG  Codec  Class"  (which  is  necessary  for
ImageDesk's  JPEG  support)  just double-click the @{b}Install@{ub} icon in the
@{b}JPEG Codec@{ub} drawer. If the @{b}JFIF DataType@{ub} by  Christoph  Feck  has  been
installed  already,  It  is  not  necessary  to  do  this installation
procedure.


@EndNode

@Node "M4_FASTE" "ImageDeskE.guide/M4_FASTE"
@Next "M5_TOUSE"
@Prev "M3_INSTL"
@Toc "Main"

Quick Start
***********

ImageDesk can be started from the Shell, or  from  the  WorkBench.  In
both cases the same arguments and tooltypes are supported.

@{b}PREFS=<FileName>@{ub}
     ImageDesk opens the prefs file @{b}<FileName>@{ub}

@{b}CATFILE=<FileName>@{ub}
     ImageDesk opens the catalog @{b}<FileName>@{ub} immediately after the
     ImageDesk startup

@{b}REXXFILE=<FileName>@{ub}
     ImageDesk executes the AREXX program @{b}<FileName>@{ub} immediately after
     the ImageDesk startup

@{b}LOGFILE=<FileName>@{ub}
     ImageDesk creates an error report file

@{b}TEMPFILE=<FileName>@{ub}
     Specifies the name for temporary files (default:
     "T:ImageDesk.temp")

@{b}VILLAGEMODE@{ub}
     For Picasso users with CyberGraphics drivers installed: ImageDesk
     starts in Village mode (normally not required).

Additionally Tooltypes allowes to assign AREXX scripts to every F-key.

@{b}Fx=<FileName>@{ub}
     The AREXX script <FileName> will be executed if Fx is pressed (<x>
     is a number between 1 and 10).

If no prefs file was specified,  ImageDesk  will  look  for  the  file
@{b}ImageDesk.idprefs@{ub} in the program directory. Should no valid prefs file
be found, ImageDesk asks via requester for the screen and font  to  be
used. If it gets all required resources, the screen will be opened and
all available functions will be accessable by the menu (and partly  by
hotkeys too).

Menu Project
............

@{b}New (<R-Amiga>+<N>)@{ub}
     First of all a requester asks for path and pattern of files to be
     processed. If this requester is confirmed positively ImageDesk
     closes the current catalog buffer, opens a new one, generates a
     thumbnail object for all selected and supported images, adds it to
     the new buffer, and lets it appear on the desk.

@{b}Open (<R-Amiga>+<O>)@{ub}
     Opens a requester which allows you to select a formerly generated
     catalog file.  An already opened catalog buffer will be closed
     first.

@{b}Close (<R-Amiga>+<C>)@{ub}
     If a catalog buffer is active it will be closed and its memory
     will be freed.

@{b}Save as... (<R-Amiga>+<S>)@{ub}
     Saves the current catalog buffer into one single file. You will be
     prompted for a file name by a requester.

@{b}Generate Catalog (<R-Amiga>+<G>)@{ub}
     Similar to @{b}New@{ub}, but additionally you will be prompted for the file
     name the catalog file will get because the catalog will be saved
     immediately. In opposition to @{b}New@{ub}, the catalog can be split into
     more partitions if necessary.

@{b}Execute Arexx (<R-Amiga>+<X>)@{ub}
     Executes the AREXX script selected in a file requester.

@{b}Information (<R-Amiga>+<I>)@{ub}
     Informs you about the current program state.

@{b}About@{ub}
     No comment.

@{b}Quit (<R-Amiga>+<Q>)@{ub}
     Quits ImageDesk after a confirmation request.

Menu Edit Buffer
................

@{b}Add Thumbnail (<R-Amiga>+<H>)@{ub}
     Asks for a file name of a picture, generates a thumbnail and adds
     it to the catalog buffer.

@{b}Add Multiple (<R-Amiga>+<U>)@{ub}
     Asks for a pattern to specify files, generates thumbnails and adds
     them to the catalog buffer.

@{b}Remove Entries... (<R-Amiga>+<E>)@{ub}
     Opens a window where the entries of the catalog buffer can be
     selected for removal.

@{b}Change Picture Path (<R-Amiga>+<&>)@{ub}
     Changes path for the catalog buffer´s pictures. The new path will
     be asked by a requester.

@{b}Update >>@{ub}
    @{b}Completely (<R-Amiga>+<K>)@{ub}
          Tries to update the catalog buffer completely.

    @{b}Only Add New (<R-Amiga>+<F>)@{ub}
          Tries to add new thumbnails for uncataloged pictures.

    @{b}Only Remove Exceeded (<R-Amiga>+<J>)@{ub}
          Removes all thumbnails which corresponding pictures do not
          exist anymore.

Menu Edit Page
..............

@{b}Redraw (<R-Amiga>+<W>)@{ub}
     Redraws the screen, unbuffered thumbnails will be lost.

@{b}Add Thumbnail (<R-Amiga>+<A>)@{ub}
     A single picture thumbnail object will be created and added to the
     current screen page. It will not be included in the catalog buffer.

@{b}Remove Thumbnail (<R-Amiga>+<R>)@{ub}
     The next selected thumbnail object will be removed from the desk.

@{b}Clean Whole Desk (<R-Amiga>+<D>)@{ub}
     After an optional confirmation request, all of the thumbnail
     objects on the desk will be removed.

@{b}Mark & Delete (<R-Amiga>+<M>)@{ub}
     First of all the thumbnail objects to be removed have to be marked
     by a mouse click. If this menu item is selected again all marked
     Thumbnails will be removed from the desk.

Menu Navigate
.............

@{b}Next Page (<Cursor right>)@{ub}
     Turns to the next screen page within the catalog buffer.

@{b}Previous Page (<Cursor left>)@{ub}
     Turns to the previous screen page within the catalog buffer.

@{b}Up One Row (<Cursor up>)@{ub}
     Scrolls up a row within the catalog buffer.

@{b}Down One Row (<Cursor down>)@{ub}
     Scrolls down a row within the catalog buffer.

@{b}Select Range... (<R-Amiga>+<L>)@{ub}
     Opens a special requester which enables you to select a range
     within the catalog buffer. All thumbnails in this range will then
     be shown.

@{b}Catalog Browser... (<R-Amiga>+<B>)@{ub}
     The catalog browser provides a quick overview of a catalog.
     Besides the thumbnail image, all available data of the
     corresponding pictures will be displayed.

Menu View Images
................

@{b}Single File (<R-Amiga>+<V>)@{ub}
     Views a choosen picture if its format is known by ImageDesk.

@{b}Path Contents (<R-Amiga>+<P>)@{ub}
     Works like @{i}Single File@{ui}, but every file name which visible in the
     file requester will be processed.

@{b}Selected Thumbnails (<R-Amiga>+<T>)@{ub}
     First of all, the desired thumbnail objects have to be marked by a
     single click on its image, after that this menu item needs to be
     selected again. Now all pictures which belong to the marked
     objects will be viewed one by one.

Menu Preferences
................

@{b}System Prefs (<R-Amiga>+<?>)@{ub}
     Opens a window for changing the system preference settings.

@{b}Viewer Prefs (<R-Amiga>+<!>)@{ub}
     Opens a window for changing the viewer preference settings.

@{b}Thumbnail Prefs (<R-Amiga>+<=>)@{ub}
     Opens a window for changing the thumbnail preference settings.

@{b}Confirmation Requests (<R-Amiga>+<,>)@{ub}
     Determinse if the user  should  be  asked  before  doing  things
     like closing the catalog buffer or removing thumbnails.

@{b}Hide Statusbar (<R-Amiga>+<.>)@{ub}
     Should the statusbar be hidden or visible.

@{b}Hide Title (<R-Amiga>+<#>)@{ub}
     Should the screen title be hidden or visible.

@{b}Load Prefs (<R-Amiga>+<Y>)@{ub}
     Load in other preference files.

@{b}Save Prefs (<R-Amiga>+<Z>)@{ub}
     Saves the current preference settings.

@{b}Reset to defaults@{ub}
     Overrides the current preference settings, and uses default
     values. Screen size and font will be asked for by a requester.


@EndNode

