@EndNode

@Node "M50" "ImageDeskE.guide/M50"
@Next "M51"
@Toc "M5_TOUSE"

Program concept
===============

This  section  should  illustrate   how   ImageDesk   handles   things
internally,    and    should    explain   some   concepts   to   avoid
misunderstandings.

As already described in the @{i}Introduction@{ui}  section,  ImageDesk  creates
small   images   from  picture  files  which  are  commonly  known  as
@{i}thumbnails@{ui}. The image of a thumbnail and some essential  data  of  the
original picture, are grouped together into a data compound which will
henceforth be called a thumbnail object.

Several thumbnail obects can be summarized  into  @{i}thumbnail  catalogs@{ui}.
Once  generated,  such  catalogs  can  be loaded or saved at any time.
Sometimes the thumbnail objects of a catalog will be called @{i}catalog
entries@{ui}.

To limit the memory consumption, and to simplify the administration, a
catalog has some restrictions

   - All thumbnail entries will have the same basic size for width and
     height.

   - The catalogs are directory oriented. This means a catalog may only
     have entries whose original pictures are stored in the same
     directory.

ImageDesk holds loaded or generated catalogs in  the  @{i}catalog  buffer@{ui}.
Starting with ImageDesk 3.0, the thumbnails of a buffered catalog will
be organized dynamically and automatically be sorted. Such  a  catalog
buffer  may  be  edited  (adding  and removing entries or updating the
catalog) and saved afterwards.

@{i}Remark:@{ui} During the generation  of  catalogs  You  won´t  see  the  the
thumbnails  immediately  sorted on the screen. But when the generation
has finished, the thumbnails will be redrawn sorted.

The visible thumbnails may be  originated  from  pictures  of  various
directories  and  there is no direct coherention of visible thumbnails
and the catalog buffer. Therefore ImageDesk has no possibility to save
all visible thumbnails into a catalog.


@EndNode

@Node "M51" "ImageDeskE.guide/M51"
@Next "M52"
@Prev "M50"
@Toc "M5_TOUSE"

Starting Imagedesk
==================

Due to my experiences, the stacksize is not growing much  higher  than
2KB.  Therefore  the  default size of 4096 Bytes will be sufficient in
most cases. If you work mainly with images much wider than 1000 pixels
it is recommended that you increase the stacksize to 8KB.

ImageDesk could be started from a shell  or  by  Workbench.  Currently
there are the following arguments and tooltypes, resp., allowed:

@{b}PREFS=<FileName>@{ub}
     ImageDesk tries to load the prefs file <FileName> at the startup.
     If this file could not be found or if it is not a valid ImageDesk
     prefs file, default values will be used. Prefs files created with
     ImageDesk 1.3 or older are not supported any longer.

@{b}CATFILE=<FileName>@{ub}
     ImageDesk opens the catalog file <FileName> immediately after
     starting up.

@{b}REXXFILE=<FileName>@{ub}
     ImageDesk executes the AREXX program <FileName> immediately after
     starting up.

@{b}LOGFILE=<FileName>@{ub}
     While ImageDesk generates thumbnail catalogs it does not allow
     requesters to pop up. To get informed about which files haven´t
     been processed, ImageDesk optionally creates an error report. This
     report is in an ASCII text file and will be saved as <FileName>.

     @{i}Tip:@{ui} This file may also be a console window.

@{b}TEMPFILE=<FileName>@{ub}
     When ImageDesk uses datatypes, it requires a temporary file to
     save this datatypes object as an IFF picture. By default its file
     name is @{b}T:ImageDesk.temp@{ub}. But if your system has not much memory,
     it is recommended not to use T: for the path of this file. In this
     case you´d better redirect this temporary file into one of your
     harddisk partitions.

@{b}VILLAGEMODE@{ub}
     (for usage with a picasso graphics board only) If the
     CyberGraphics software is installed on the system, ImageDesk will
     use it for its special screens in 8/15/16 or 24 bitdepth by
     default. if VILLAGEMODE is set, it will try to use the emulated
     Picasso drivers instead. Should be ignored in most cases.

Additionally Tooltypes allowes to assign AREXX scripts to every F-key.

@{b}Fx=<FileName>@{ub}
     The AREXX script <FileName> will be executed if Fx is pressed (<x>
     is a number between 1 and 10).

If no configuration file has been specified at programstart, ImageDesk
will  try to find the file @{b}ImageDesk.idprefs@{ub} in the program directory.
The first time you  start  ImageDesk  it  won't,  of  course,  find  a
configuration  file.  In this case ImageDesk reports about it, and you
will be asked for screen mode and screen font. The other  values  will
be  set  to defaults. Before exiting ImageDesk asks you for saving the
last used preference settings. If ImageDesk is started the first time,
it  is  recommended  to  set  all  the  preferences values to your own
requirements by selecting the menu items @{b}System Prefs@{ub},  @{b}Viewer  Prefs@{ub},
and @{b}ThumbNail Prefs@{ub} (see also @{i}Configuration@{ui}).


@EndNode

@Node "M52" "ImageDeskE.guide/M52"
@Next "M53"
@Prev "M51"
@Toc "M5_TOUSE"

Configuration
=============

The configuration adjustments in ImageDesk have been splitted in three
major groups:

   @{b}*@{ub} System preferences

   @{b}*@{ub} Viewer preferences

   @{b}*@{ub} Thumbnail preferences

Therefore, three preferences windows are available:


 @{" System Prefs     " Link "M521"}     
 @{" Viewer Prefs     " Link "M522"}     
 @{" Thumbnail Prefs  " Link "M523"} 


@EndNode

@Node "M521" "ImageDeskE.guide/M521"
@Next "M522"
@Toc "M52"

System Prefs
------------

The valid screen mode data is displayed in the frame titled @{i}Screen@{ui}.  A
mouse  click on the @{b}?@{ub}-button opens a screen mode requester where a new
screen mode can be selected. It is  also  possible  to  choose  higher
values  for  width and height than the screen's visible sizes. In this
case it will be opened as an autoscroll screen.

The frame titled @{i}Font@{ui} can be handled the same way. Here, the font  for
the  screen  and  the  windows  of  ImageDesk  is displayed and can be
changed.

@{i}Caution:@{ui} If screen mode or font has been changed and  you  leave  this
window  by  pressing  the @{b}USE@{ub} or @{b}SAVE@{ub} button, all unbuffered thumbnail
objects will be lost.

The third framed area of this window groups some gadgets where you can
choose  the  XPK mode to use, an encryption password if supported, and
specify the efficiency of packing.  If  XPK  is  not  installed  these
gadgets are disabled.

Other preference gadgets which could not be classified to a specific
group are:

@{b}Save Project Icons@{ub}
     This gadget determines if an icon should be created for each
     generated catalog file. Creating project icons for each catalog
     file has a big advantage. Later, it is possible to start ImageDesk
     and load a catalog file with a single mouse click.

@{b}Use Datatypes@{ub}
     If activated, ImageDesk tries to read all unrecognized files with
     the help of datatypes.

@{b}Use XPK for Catalogs@{ub}
     This gadget is displayed disabled if XPK has not been installed.
     Otherwise, it determines if XPK is used for saving catalog files.

@{b}Print Execution Command@{ub}
     This Gadget is significant if extenal viewers are used. If it is
     selected, the executed command will be printed in the output
     window.

@{b}Default Action@{ub}
     This cycle gadget determines what happens if a thumbnail object has
     been clicked. Possible choices are:

        - View Image - Views the corresponding image immediately.

        - Execute AREXX - Runs an AREXX script, specified in @{b}Default
          AREXX Script@{ub}. The script will receive file name, image type
          of the original picture and the position on the screen.

        - Requester - An information window opens which shows all
          essential attributes of the image represented by the clicked
          thumbnail object:

             @{b}*@{ub} File name of the original image

             @{b}*@{ub} Path of the file

             @{b}*@{ub} Type of the image (IFF, JPEG, GIF...)

             @{b}*@{ub} Image width in pixels

             @{b}*@{ub} Image height in pixels

             @{b}*@{ub} Original bitdepth of the image

             @{b}*@{ub} Does the image file contain a color palette

          Clicking the button @{b}Very Interesting@{ub} will close the window and
          nothing else will happen. The buttons @{b}View Image@{ub} and @{b}Execute
          AREXX@{ub} will operate as described above.

@{b}Default AREXX Script@{ub}
     This string gadget is used to specify the AREXX script which has
     to be executed if @{b}Default Action@{ub} is set to @{b}Execute AREXX@{ub}. Clicking
     the @{b}?@{ub}-button opens a file requester for choosing the script name.

@{b}Output Window@{ub}
     Here the string for specifiying the attributes of the external
     viewer console window has to be edited. It is very important for
     this string to contain @{b}SCREEN=IMAGEDESK@{ub} at the end. Otherwise,
     this console window won't open on ImageDesk's screen.

@{b}Max. entries per catalog@{ub}
     This is a slider gadget which allows you to change the entry limit
     of the catalog files. If a scanned directory contains more entries
     than specified here, enough catalog files will be generated as
     necessary to store all of its thumbnails. Should more than one
     catalog file be used for a single scan, the files will be numbered
     and its filename will get this number as a file name extension.

There are four additional buttons, horizontaly spreaded at the bottom of
the window:

@{b}Save@{ub}
     The current configuration will be saved, the window is closed, and
     the changed values will be used in ImageDesk.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     The edited configuration is used immediately and the window is
     closed.

@{b}Load@{ub}
     You will be prompted in a filerequestor for a prefs file which is
     loaded afterwards.  The window remains open to let the user make
     further changes to the loaded prefs.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     The window is closed, all changes will be dismissed.


@EndNode

@Node "M522" "ImageDeskE.guide/M522"
@Next "M523"
@Prev "M521"
@Toc "M52"

Viewer Prefs
------------

This window is used to select which viewer is used for each supported
image format. To select, click on one radio button for @{b}custom screen@{ub},
@{b}external@{ub} or @{b}window@{ub}.

@{i}Remarks:@{ui}
   @{b}*@{ub} If the `Tower JPEG Codec' has not been installed, the corresponding
     buttons are disabled.

   @{b}*@{ub} There are no prefs for a datatypes viewer because such readed
     images will be convertet into IFFs. Therefore the IFF-prefs are
     also valid for images readed with the help of datatypes.

To specify an external viewer, you have to type the viewer name and the
arguments you want to use. Instead of a file name type @{b}%s@{ub}.  A small
example:

Suppose you want to use the picture viewer called @{i}GigaView@{ui} and usally
you would call this viewer by typing:

                  GigaView <FileName> SCREENBEHIND
In the corresponding gadget you would have to type the following string:

                  GigaView %s SCREENBEHIND

@{i}Caution:@{ui} you have to use the whole path instead of the viewer name
only. Otherwise ImageDesk may not find it.

The preferences in the framed area named @{i}Internal Viewer Prefs@{ui} are
meaningless for external viewers and partly meaningless for most image
formats.

@{b}Display Screens@{ub}
     With this cycle gadget you tell ImageDesk how to determine the
     custom screens for displaying the images.

        -     @{i}autoscreen@{ui} - ImageDesk tries to find optimal values for
          screen mode and screen size by itself.

        -     @{i}requester@{ui} - Everytime an image has to be displayed, the
          user will be asked for a screen mode by a requester.

        -     @{i}global@{ui} - Fixed screen IDs will be used. The user is
          responsible for @{i}Global CLUT Screen@{ui} and @{i}Global DCOL Screen@{ui} to
          have valid values.

@{b}Display Size@{ub}
     Which size the images should be displayed in is set here.  These
     values are meaningless for the external viewers.

        -     @{i}original@{ui} - The image will be displayed in original size.

        -     @{i}small@{ui} - The image will be displayed in half the hight and
          half the width.

        -     @{i}tiny@{ui} - The image will be displayed in a quarter the hight
          and a quarter the width.  @{i}Caution:@{ui} The values in @{b}Display Size@{ub}
     are only meaningful for the image formats PCD and JPEG.

@{b}Orientation@{ub}
     These adjustments will cause the following:

        -     @{i}Auto@{ui} - Tries to find out the orientation by itself.

        -     @{i}Force Landscape@{ui} - PCD only: Displays images in landscape
          mode.

        -     @{i}Force Portrait@{ui} - PCD only: Displays images in portrait
          mode.

        -     @{i}Upside Down@{ui} - Displays images mirrored to the x-axxis.

        -     @{i}Left to Right@{ui} - PCD only: Displays images mirrored to the
          y-axxis.

@{b}Global CLUT Screen@{ub}
     After clicking on the @{b}?@{ub}-button a screen requester appears where you
     have to choose an 8-bit screen. This selected screen mode is used
     for displaying all images containing up to 256 colors. This
     setting is only significant if @{i}Display Screens@{ui} is set to @{i}global@{ui}.

@{b}Global DCOL Screen@{ub}
     Same as @{i}Global CLUT Screen@{ui}, with the difference that a screen mode
     for all images containing more than 256 colors has to be choosen.

     @{i}Remark:@{ui} it is quite possible to choose an 8-bit screen mode, but
     the display quality will be not very satisfying.

@{b}Dither 8-Bit Displays@{ub}
     If this gadget is checked, the images in 8 bit illustration (this
     is valid for the window viewers and for the 8-bit screen viewers)
     are displayed dithered. This improves the display quality of the
     image, but slows down the procedure a bit. Only images which
     contain more than 256 colors will be dithered. This means all
     15/16/24/32 bit pictures and HAM images.

@{b}Use Original Palette@{ub}
     If checked, this gadget says that the window viewers will use the
     original color palette of the pictures. Therefore, it is
     meaningful for images which only contain up to 256 colors. If `Use
     Original Palette' is activated, ImageDesk temporarily switches its
     palette to the one of the picture. This will cause a somewhat
     strange looking user interface but it will decrease the the time
     for building up an image @{i}dramatically@{ui} and will avoid quality
     losses. In the other case the image will be converted to 24-bit
     RGB row by row and scaled to 8-bit RGB, afterwards (for the
     insiders: RRRGGGBB).

@{b}SuperBitMap Window@{ub}
     If checked the Window viewer opens its Window as a
     "SuperBitmapWindow".  The SuperBitmap window has the advantage
     that the picture is visible during reading, but it needs much more
     system resources and causes scrolling problems on CyberGfx screens.

@{b}Delay@{ub}
     The maximum duration time an image has to be displayed (in 1/10
     seconds).  After all, the display could be closed at any time (any
     keystroke or mouse button when screen viewers are used, ESC-key or
     CloseGadget when the Window viewers are used).

The four additional buttons @{b}SAVE@{ub}, @{b}USE@{ub}, @{b}LOAD@{ub} and @{b}CANCEL@{ub} have the same
meaning as they have in the System Prefs window.


@EndNode

@Node "M523" "ImageDeskE.guide/M523"
@Prev "M522"
@Toc "M52"

Thumbnail Prefs
---------------

In this window it has to be choosen how the thumbnail objects have to be
presented or rendered.

The upper three gadgets are responsible for the font which is used for
printing the file name below a thumbnail image (if desired). This font
has to be selected the same way as described in @{i}System Prefs@{ui}.

The next four gadgets have the following meaning:

@{b}Show File Names@{ub}
     If selected, file names will be displayed below the thumbnail
     images.

@{b}HiQuality@{ub}
     This switch is just relevant for the formats PCD and JPEG. If it is
     activated the original images will be used for calculating the
     thumbnail images instead of reading them in already scaled.

     @{i}Remark:@{ui} HiQuality requires much more memory and rendering time
     while calculating thumbnail images for the above mentioned formats.

@{b}Dither Method@{ub}
     Since ImageDesk has to deal with a limited number of colors, the
     thumbnail images are not always in the best quality, especially if
     the images contain fine colour runs. If @{b}FLOYD@{ub} or @{b}ORDERED@{ub} has been
     selected in this cycle gadget, a bigger colorspace is simulated by
     the use of dithering.  However, using dithering does not always
     result in a better quality of the thumbnail images, as the
     pixelspace is to small to cheat the eyes perfectly.

@{b}Thumbnail Size@{ub}
     This cycle gadget determines the basic size of the thumbnails.

     @{i}Remark:@{ui} For performance and quality reasons the thumbnail images
     won't always get exactly the specified size.

The four additional buttons @{b}SAVE@{ub}, @{b}USE@{ub}, @{b}LOAD@{ub} and @{b}CANCEL@{ub} have the same
meaning as they have in the other prefs windows.

@{i}Caution:@{ui} If you have made changes in this window, it may be necessary
to remove all active thumbnail objects from the screen. Otherwise all
changes will be dismissed.


@EndNode

@Node "M53" "ImageDeskE.guide/M53"
@Next "M54"
@Prev "M52"
@Toc "M5_TOUSE"

Menu
====


 @{" Project " Link "M531"}     
 @{"         Edit Buffer " Link "M532"}     
 @{"                     Edit Page " Link "M533"}     
 @{"                               Navigate " Link "M534"}     
 @{"                                        View Images " Link "M535"}     
