@Node "M54" "ImageDeskE.guide/M54"
@Next "M55"
@Prev "M53"
@Toc "M5_TOUSE"

Restrictions
============

Without a personal key file, ImageDesk does not offer its whole
functionality.  The restrictions in particular:

   @{b}*@{ub} Sometimes a @{i}NervRequester@{ui} will appear.

   @{b}*@{ub} The generation of catalogs is limited to 39 entries.

   @{b}*@{ub} ImageDesk reads 38 thumbnail entries per catalog at most.

   @{b}*@{ub} The funtction @{b}Save as...@{ub} is disabled.

   @{b}*@{ub} Updating catalogs is disabled.

   @{b}*@{ub} The catalog tool @{b}CATJoin@{ub} won't work without a key file.

You can read about how to get a personal key file in @{i}How to Register@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "M55" "ImageDeskE.guide/M55"
@Prev "M54"
@Toc "M5_TOUSE"

Hints on usage
==============

Memory shortages
----------------

Starting with ImageDesk 2.0 catalogs will be held in memory, which  is
the  basis  for  a  quick turn over of screen pages. This additionally
memory consumption  may  cause  memory  shortages  on  lower  equipped
systems.  In this case the first step sould be to redirect ImageDesk´s
temporary file to a device which doesn´t use system memory @{i}(see also
Tooltypes)@{ui}.

Also avoid large catalog buffers. The system prefs setting @{i}max. entries
per catalog@{ui} will help you on this.

Renounce using XPK when saving or generating catalogs.  ImageDesk  3.0
handles  its  catalog  buffer in another way than older versions. When
using XPK compression, this makes it neccessary  to  occupy  a  second
temporary  catalog  buffer  with the same size as the original catalog
buffer. To compress saved catalogs you can alternately  use  the  tool
CATREPACK afterwards.

Using XPK
---------

If you have enough memory, it is recommended to  use  XPK  compression
for  saving catalogs.The files will be shrunk to 35% of their original
size on the average. This shrink factor may be brought down to 25%  if
certain  XPK  mode  and efficiency have been choosen. Furthermore, XPK
provides password protection for catalog files. Yet for all,  that  it
has to be considered, your password is stored unencrypted in the prefs
file and could be read by  anyone  who  has  access  to  the  computer
system. The following XPK methods are very useful.

   -     @{b}SHRI@{ub} - provides very high packing rates

   -     @{b}RDCN@{ub} - provides very fast packing

   -     @{b}MASH@{ub} - provides quick packing with high rates

@{i}Caution:@{ui} Don't use @{b}xpack@{ub} for packing or repacking catalog files,
ImageDesk won't be able to read them then. Use @{b}CATRepack@{ub} instead.

Datatypes
---------

It is possible to renounce on datatypes support (@{i}see System Prefs@{ui}). If
you  only work with images, ImageDesk recognizes internally it is even
recommended because it speeds up ImageDesk a bit.

Besides this, Datatypes support has  the  side-effect  that  undesired
files  like icons or fonts also will be cataloged if the corresponding
datatype is installed.

Online Help
-----------

ImageDesk does not support an internal online help function, but this
could be done external very simply:

check the tooltypes in the icon of the hypertext document
@{b}ImageDesk.guide@{ub}. If it has not been done before, set a tooltype
variable to @{b}PUBSCREEN=IMAGEDESK@{ub}.

If you need help after ImageDesk has been started you have to switch to
the Workbench Screen (@{b}<Left-Amiga>+<m>@{ub}) and double-click the icon
@{b}ImageDesk.guide@{ub}.

ImageDesk Windows
-----------------

Everytime the current configuration is saved, the size and position of
certain  ImageDesk  windows are saved with it. The last used positions
and sizes will be stored here. If the font or screen size has  changed
in  the  meantime  it  may  be  necessary to override these values for
opening the windows properly.

Screen Colors
-------------

ImageDesk uses an optimized color palette. 255  out  of  256  possible
colors are reserved for figuring the thumbnail images. Therefore it is
not possible to let the user choose custom colors for ImageDesk's user
interface.  Another  consequence of this fixed palette are the unusual
colors the mouse pointer will get.

PCD support
-----------

The PCD support in ImageDesk is just rudimentary, because there is  no
public  PCD  documentation  available.  A licence is very expensiv and
just affordable for commercial developers.

All used information on the PCD format, I got from studying  pertinent
source  codes  or  I  found  out by myself. If you want to have a more
professional  Photo  CD(TM)  support  you   should   consider   buying
commercial  product.  Thereby  you'll get access to the larger formats
1536x1024, 3072x2048 (and even bigger) and  to  image  converting  and
processing functions.

Changing the default project icon
---------------------------------

If you don't like the icons generated by  ImageDesk  (maybe  you  need
`MagicWB'-style  icons),  you  just  have  to  change  the  icon named
@{b}ID_DefProjIcon(.info)@{ub}. This could be done with  pertinent  icon  tools
e.g.  @{b}IconEd@{ub}.  But  you should consider not changing the icon's
attributes and also not to fix them.


@EndNode

@Node "M6_AREXX" "ImageDeskE.guide/M6_AREXX"
@Next "M7_TOOLS"
@Prev "M5_TOUSE"
@Toc "Main"

AREXX Port
**********


 @{" Miscellaneous       " Link "M61"}    

 @{" Conventions         " Link "M62"}    

 @{" Command references  " Link "M63"} 


@EndNode

@Node "M61" "ImageDeskE.guide/M61"
@Next "M62"
@Toc "M6_AREXX"

Miscellaneous
=============

Since version 1.5 ImageDesk consists of an AREXX port. Such  an  AREXX
port has several advantages.

   - ImageDesk can be controlled by a script file

   - ImageDesk is able to communicate with other programs

   - ImageDesk can be controlled by other programs

   - It is possible to extend ImageDesks command set

There are several possibilities for starting ImageDesk AREXX scripts.

  a. By executing the AmigaDos command "rx <Scriptfile>" in the command
     line

  b. Immediately on program start by using ImageDesk's command line
     arguments (ImageDesk R=<Scriptfile>)

  c. Immediately on program start by using ImageDesk's tooltypes
     (REXX=<Scriptfile>)

  d. By selecting the menu item "Execute AREXX" in the menu "Project"

  e. By clicking into a thumbnail object (if selected in @{b}System Prefs@{ub})

  f. By clicking the @{i}AREXX@{ui} button in the @{i}Catalog Browser@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "M62" "ImageDeskE.guide/M62"
@Next "M63"
@Prev "M61"
@Toc "M6_AREXX"

Conventions
===========

Each AREXX script for ImageDesk which has been started by a) to d) has
to begin with the following lines:

     /* --------------------- standard startup ----------------------- */
     
     OPTIONS RESULTS
     
     if( ADDRESS() ~= "IDESK_REXXPORT" ) then
         ADDRESS IDESK_REXXPORT
     
     /* -------------------------------------------------------------- */

AREXX scripts which are thought to be executed on thumbnail click will
receive three arguments from ImageDesk.

   @{b}*@{ub} file name of the corresponding image

   @{b}*@{ub} image type (IFF, GIF, JPG, PCX, BMP, PCD, PNM or TGA)

   @{b}*@{ub} a position number

Therefore those AREXX programs should begin like this:

     /* ---- standard startup II (if started via thumbnail click) ---- */
     
     OPTIONS RESULTS
     
     PARSE ARG iname itype thpos
     
     /* -------------------------------------------------------------- */

All AREXX commands and keywords if supported have to be  in  uppercase
letters. Up to four arguments are supported. Some of the commands show
a different behavior,  depending  on  the  number  of  arguments  (for
example OPENCAT). Arguments containing spaces have to be quoted. Since
AREXX is filtering these quotation marks out of static  strings,  they
have to be forced by embedding the quoted string in "'"s in this case.

Example
.......

     OPENCAT '"ram disk:pics.cat"'

If a string is stored in an  AREXX  variable  the  string  has  to  be
embedded explicitely in quotation marks.

Example
.......

     StringVar = "This is a requester"
     IDREQUEST OK '"'||StringVar||'"'

Some of the AREXX commands will return a result string  which  can  be
found in the global AREXX variable "RESULT"

Example
.......

     GETSYSINFO DESKPLACE
     deskplace = RESULT

In addition to a result string you will get a return  code  from  from
the commands. If a command has been executed properly without an error
this will be the value 0. If the number of delivered arguments was not
right for a specific command, the return code will be 10. If a command
has been canceled by the user or an error  occured,  you  will  get  a
return  code of 5. The return code can be requested through the global
AREXX variable "RC"

Example
.......

     IDGETFILE "Select a file"
     if RC > 0 then exit /* User has choosen "cancel" */
     filename = RESULT

Boolean values have to be made available as one of the strings  "TRUE"
or  "FALSE"  (uppercase!).  Commands which return boolean values, will
return them as strings, too.

Example
.......

     SETVPREFS DITHER TRUE


@EndNode

